Paper Analysis: Analytics for Insurance Fraud: An Empirical Study

The paper focuses its work on deriving a framework that companies can use to detect fraud. Specifically, it tries to: 1. Identify key significant variables in fraud 2. Put together a point system to detect business value from fraud and 3. Put together a final framework using the point system in order for comapnies to use in their fraud detection approaches.

First, the authors identified 20 key variables out of 31 using chi-square and t-test approaches to determine significance. After that, they broke down their framework into 4 different groupings (demographic, claim, vehicle, Policy Type). Each grouping had a collection of binary questions that supported a significance in the claim potentially being fraudulent. All questions were either a 1 or 0 and collected together, made a point system with a maximum of 20. The idea behind the framework is that any company can apply this system and create a threshold for themselves for which they should investigate a claim further for potential fraud.

The best qualities of the paper was how interpretable it was as well as how simple it is to apply it on a broad scale. An insurance company would have no troubles simply implementing the rules set out by the framework. What could have been better is the detail that was used in determining some of the point system questions and the underlying modeling to identifying those questions as significant.

Lead:

Firstly, we will look at the time based variables that are in the dataset. Variables around the time will allow us to better identify trend in time for type of transactions and the consistencies of transactions that occur through time. Time based variables created will allow our model to identify spikes in claims or types of transactions to a time of year, which can be critical to finding an outlier that may ultimately be a fraudulent claim. We will first put the transaction date feature into a YY-MM-DD format and see the range of time that the dataset deals with. Then we will look at the count of transactions that are in the dataset through time as well as the amount that was spent through time. Finally, there will be two variables created, one for a categorical grouping, starting from 1- which will for transactions that happened in the earliest quarter in the dataset and ending at 4- which are the transactions in the last quarter of the dataset. Finally, there will be a variable - TD - created which will be a numeric value denoting the amount of days since the last day covered in the dataset (6/30/14).

        main="Amount through time",las=2       )

#Categorized transactions based on the quartile of the last transaction dates (4- most recent)
r_score <- ifelse(ccard$Transaction_Date < '2013-09-25', 1, 
                              ifelse(ccard$Transaction_Date > '2013-09-26' & 
                                       ccard$Transaction_Date <"2014-01-06", 2, 
                                                ifelse(ccard$Transaction_Date > '2014-01-07' & 
                                                         ccard$Transaction_Date < "2014-04-02", 3, 4)))
ccard <- cbind(ccard, r_score)

#Getting the difference in time
ccard <- ccard %>% 
  mutate(TD = difftime('2014-06-30', ccard$Transaction_Date, units="days")) #Last date in the dataset (6/30) and subtracting from date
summary(ccard$TD)
##   Length    Class     Mode 
##   442458 difftime  numeric

Conclusion:

In order to find anomalies that may indicate fraud, time is a critical component to use in our analysis as it will be able to group together. By looking at the difference of count thrugh time vs amount, we are able to see that while the count remains relatively consistent, there are two very large spikes on 8/21 and 7/19 in 2013. With this information, we created two variables, one grouping the transaction date into quartiles of nearest to oldest and a numeric based variable based on amount of days since the last day covered in the dataset (6/30/2014).

Conclusion:

There are clear patterns that arise from the type of purchases that are made. For example, some of the logical conclusions that stick out are:

  • Computers and software were the third most in regards to the amount paid however they were not bought as many time

  • Book stores and stationary/ office supplies tend to have a lot of purchases but not a lot of money spent in them

Observations that do not seem to align with logical assumptions:

  • Medical proedcures like Dental are high in terms of count and amount. While it makes sense that there would be a lot of money spent on medical procedures, logic would dictate that these elements would be lower in the amount of times that they were bought.

  • Grand River Dam had a very large uptick in transactions and was responsible for the most expensive purchases starting in the 2nd quarter through the end of the dataset With this information and the groupings provided above, there should be a cross-validation of these three features (and the time of their purchases) with the indipendant variable of the dataset.

Lead:

Next we will look at the consumer side of the equation. We will look at the last name, and then combine the first initial to see if there is a significant difference when comparing the the more specific ‘Full_Name’ metric. This is an important feature as it will allow us to pinpoint a fraud case when it occurs from the consumer side. Its important to note that applying this approach on a grander scale in operation has some ethical risks. These risks arise from the fact that names, particularly for that of individuals, can have correlations with certain types of purchases and actions based on their culture or other factors. Due to this risk, applying models to a feature like the name of the consumer can sometimes garner significance behind when there isnt much of it.

First, the count of how many purchases were done by customer tended to lean towards corporations in the top three (Specifically Jurney Huse Travel and American University), with individual buyers coming in afterwards. Nonetheless, this variables will be useful in specying cases of fraud once variables are further broken down and more understood.

Conclusion:

By taking a look at vendors and their corresponding consumers we are able to glean important details in regards to sizes and tendencies of transactions. The variables were looked at individually by vendor and then collectively by the grouping of Vendor and Agency_Name. The immediate outliers were the adjustment payments that were paid by medically services and then the very large amount of transactions that occured by some vendors.

Logical observations:

  • Large Ecommerce giants such as Amazon, Lowes, and Staples had many purchases for relatively low per purchase transactions
  • The largest individual transactions were generally administrative from large organizations such as universities and health centers.

Observations that do not seem to align with logical assumptions:

  • Bill Warren Office, which is a relatively small supplier, had a very large amount of transactions that far outnumbered those of larger competitors.
  • The per transaction costs of some purchases could signal avenue for potential fraud. For example, Grand Rive Dam agency has many purchases for large amount of value on a consistent basis.

Final Conclusion:

  • Time Based Variables: We were able to outline the timeline of transactions of this dataset while identifying spikes in major transactions amount during an otherwise consistent count of purchases. In addition, being able to categorize timelines per quarter of the timeline of the dataset. Finally, having a variable showing the difference in time from the most recent transaction will be useful in identifying anomalies in purchasing by customers.
  • Frequency of transactions: We looked at the Merchant Category and were able to identify the anomalies when it comes to logical and illogical pairings of transactions. This was then couple with looking at the name variables to align the most common purchasers as well as the highest spenders per transaction. Being able to group the tendencies of frequency and size of a purchase to a specific buyer will allow us to identify the anomalies which could signal fraud much more efficiently.
  • Monetary value and realtionship to Vendors/ Custmers: We focused on the vendor side to give us an outline of who the sellers are in this dataset and how the tendency of their transactions look. Adding the average purchase and comapring it to the number of transactions and total amount spent gave us an important perspective. Specifically, the per transaction purchases tended to cluster around large conglomorate e-commerce customers while the largest individual purchasers were generally from corporations. Nonetheless, the identification of a buyer grouped and compared with these factors will give us the estimates needed to be able to more confidently identify fraud.

Some of the variables that I hope to include in more detail once we start creating predictive models are description, and the type of transaction (which this dataset did not have). These elements, including the ones discussed here such as time, frequency, amount purchased, and the categorization of buyers/ sellers will be excellent predictors of credit card fraud.
